<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-472-800  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 472 800.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  July 24 1989 v8 n15 p94(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSBCA extends jurisdiction into agency policies. (Fedwatch)(General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals )(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services AdministrationManagementGovernment RegulationGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GSBCA Extends Jurisdiction Into Agency PoliciesandM;In a major expansion of its jurisdiction, the General Services AdministrationBoard of Contract Appeals ruled it can hear cases that claim violation ofinternal agency management policy.andM;This means the GSBCA will go beyond enforcing acquisition regulations such asthe Federal Information Resources Management Regulations (FIRMR), the FederalAcquisition Regulations (FAR), the Defense FAR and other agency supplements.andM;Every GSA delegation of procurement authority requires the agency to follow&quot;federal statutes, policies and regulations governing the acquisition,management and utilization of ADP resources.&quot;andP;  If a vendor thinks an agencyhas violated this DPA provision, it can file a protest under the board'sruling in case 10066-P, dated June 30.andM;In this case, the GSBCA determined that the Defense Logistics Agency hadviolated an internal Defense Department memorandum issued in 1980, whichrequired approval from the Office of the Secretary of Defense for &quot;proposedprocurements.&quot;andM;DLA sought the approval after it had issued the request for proposals.andP;  Theagency said it was urgent that a new RFP be issued because the originalcontract with C3 Inc., Herndon, Va., had been terminated.andP;  The board did notaccept this excuse, stating that the violation was deliberate.andP;  C3's motionfor summary relief wasgranted.andM;This expansion of GSBCA's jurisdiction into internal agency policies couldhave far-reaching impact on federal ADP acquisitions.andP;  Every agency, bureau,field activity, procurement office, division and branch has policies andprocedures that dictate how each performs its function.andP;  Clearly, some ofthese policies are extensions of federal procurement regulations and arecodified in the FAR and its supplements.andM;Other policies are more geared toward management than procurement, such ascompliance with an organization's standard ADP equipment architecture orinvestigating sharing opportunities before buying new equipment.andM;For now, this ruling establishes the possibility that a vendor can protest aviolation of any of these internal policies.andP;  As a result, agency personnelmust ensure that all such policies are followed, not just those in the FARand FIRMR.andO;</TEXT></DOC>